  "prompt": "What is the defence mechanism in plants?",
  "response": "Plants have several defense mechanisms to protect themselves against various threats, including pathogens, herbivores, and environmental stresses. Here are some key defense mechanisms:\n\n1. Physical Barriers\n- Thick cell walls\n- Waxy cuticle\n- Thorns and spines\n- Trichomes (hair-like structures)\n\n2. Chemical Defenses\n- Toxic compounds\n- Bitter or unpalatable substances\n- Phenolic compounds\n- Alkaloids\n- Tannins\n- Terpenoids\n- Latex production\n\n3. Systemic Acquired Resistance (SAR)\n- Develop resistance to subsequent pathogen attacks\n- Activate defense genes throughout the plant\n- Produce salicylic acid and other signaling molecules\n\n4. Hypersensitive Response\n- Localized cell death to prevent pathogen spread\n- Rapid response to infection\n- Creates barriers around infected areas\n\n5. Induced Mechanical Barriers\n- Callose deposition\n- Cell wall reinforcement\n- Lignification\n\n6. Phytohormone-mediated Defense\n- Jasmonic acid\n- Salicylic acid\n- Ethylene\n\n7. RNA Interference\n- Silencing viral genes\n- Preventing pathogen replication\n\nThese mechanisms help plants survive and protect themselves from various environmental challenges.",
